Role of Piezo channels in mechanotransduction {#sec1-2045894018767393}
=============================================

Mechanotransduction is defined as a process by which cells convert a mechanical stimulus into electrical or chemical signals which allow the cells to adapt to mechanical changes in the *milieu*. Mechanosensitive channels are transmembrane proteins that respond to mechanical stress over a wide dynamic range of external mechanical stimuli. Among these, Piezo channels—primarily Piezo1 and Piezo2—have emerged as key mediators of mechanotransduction in various cell types. These large, trimeric ion channels are directly gated by mechanical forces applied to the cell membrane, such as stretch, shear stress, or pressure. Upon activation, Piezo channels allow the influx of cations, including calcium and sodium, leading to membrane depolarization and subsequent intracellular signaling cascades.

