Introduction {#sec1}
============

An estimated 100 million men worldwide experience subfertility ([@ref19]), yet for many, the precise underlying causes remain unknown. Successful natural fertilization depends on sperm’s ability to navigate the female reproductive tract, a process driven by complex flagellar motion. Despite this, standard assessments of sperm motility typically focus only on tracking the position of the sperm head, neglecting the detailed mechanics of the flagellum itself. As a result, clinicians and researchers may struggle to differentiate between sperm that appear to swim normally but harbor subtle flagellar defects and those that are genuinely healthy. To address this gap, there is a pressing need for diagnostic tools that capture both head trajectories and the nuanced dynamics of flagellar beating. Encouragingly, recent progress in imaging technology, computational analysis, and biophysical modeling is beginning to shed light on these intricate movements. These advances offer the potential not only to improve diagnostic precision and prognostic evaluation but also to guide more effective, individualized interventions for male infertility.

